## The Pendant Sweet Spot

A ring needs to be visible at arm's length. Earrings need to be visible at face distance — about 18 to 24 inches. Pendants hang somewhere in between.

Your pendant sits at the collarbone or just below. That puts it 16 to 18 inches down from your face. People looking at you see it from 2 to 4 feet away. That viewing distance changes which carat size makes sense.

At 1/4 ct: subtle. You can tell it's a diamond but it reads small even up close. Good for people who want something delicate and barely-there.

At 1/2 ct: visible but still understated. Nice everyday look. Not a statement.

At 3/4 ct: solid middle ground. Clearly a diamond pendant from normal conversation distance.

At 1 ct: this is The Pendant Sweet Spot. Clearly visible from 3 feet away. You see the shape. You see it sparkle. It reads as real jewelry without being oversized for most occasions. Works for work, dinner, and dressier events.

At 2 ct: statement territory. The first thing you notice. Right for special occasions or people who want their pendant to be visible across a room.

At 3 ct: fine jewelry presence. Reserved for buyers who want the pendant to be the centerpiece of an outfit.

Chain length also matters here. An 18-inch chain is the sweet spot for most pendant sizes — it sits just below the collarbone. For a 1ct cushion pendant, 18 inches gives the stone room to hang and show. For a 2ct or 3ct pendant, a 20-inch chain lets the stone sit with more visual space on the chest, which suits a larger stone better.

